snippet: In Sevastopol, a pro-Ukraine rally of hundreds was attacked by pro-Russia supporters, who had their own rally there, while Ukraine celebrated the birth of its greatest poet in the Crimean capital.
abstract: Competing rallies turn violent in Ukraine; tens of thousands gather in Kiev to celebrate 200th anniversary of birth of Taras Shevchenko, a poet who is a symbol of Ukrainian nationhood, while in Sevastopol, Crimea, a pro-Ukraine rally attended by several hundred people is attacked by pro-Russia supporters.

byline.original: By STEVEN ERLANGER and ELLEN BARRY
byline.contributor: Steven Erlanger reported from Kiev, and Ellen Barry from Moscow. Reporting was contributed by Andrew Roth from Donetsk, Ukraine; Noah Sneider and Patrick Reevell from Crimea, Ukraine; and Brian Knowlton from Washington.

lead_paragraph: In Sevastopol, a pro-Ukraine rally of hundreds was attacked by pro-Russia supporters, who had their own rally there, while Ukraine celebrated the birth of its greatest poet in the Crimean capital.

headline.main: Clashes in Ukraine as Rallies Take a Turn
